@Mark
Yes, same here. NYT app (not Games app) on iPhone. During the last few days, the GamePlay / WordPlay / time stats are no longer available in the usual way. No problem accessing the games themselves. So far I’m resisting installing the Games app, guessing the old functionality will come back in the next version of the NYT app. My workaround is to Search for ‘wordplay’ which gets me access to recent articles by Sam / Deb / Caitlin.
🎱

@SBK

😂

More importantly, I didn't donate fifty million to the "inauguration" festivities for my current ruler.

@Seb
Well.....since 6 is spelt SEIS in Spanish, I'd say the gap remains...

The acquisition of Puerto Rico (turn of the century,) the influx of Cuban refugees (60's), the flow of immigrants (ongoing), not to mention the history of settlement in the Southwest (lands originally claimed and settled by Spainish forces invading ancestral "First People's" territories)...  make Spanish a rather sensible study for US residents/students.

@pedant

Why so intolerant? Some people choose to change their name when they get married. Men do it, too, albeit more rarely than women. The reasons are multiple, and there doesn't have to be anything nefarious about them.

My wife kept her name. I offered to take a double-barreled one myself, but she didn't want me to. My mother added my father's name to hers. All these choices made freely.

@Andrzej

I actually feel embarrassed that both my former wife and my current wife so easily consented to taking my last name.

In fact, it never came up for discussion.

@Andrzej

Tacit consent.  I never even thought to ask (which also embarrasses me). 

It was just the way the process flows.  At least in 1994.  I know much less about 2025.

@pedant

If names imply ownership, then my last name at birth came from my first owner, my father. When I got married, I appended my husband’s last name, so now I guess I have two owners.

Except I don’t. The names that each of us keep, add to, or change are the result of individual choice. To suggest otherwise is not only offensive, it’s a bit, shall I say… patronizing.

@Heidi

Love your point about your father owning you with your first last name!  

Personally, I changed my former last name to my middle name, so I have two middle names now, and took on my husband's last name. Grateful for choices!!

@Francis

I know a lot of friends who were getting married in the early '90s, and I was the bridesmaid for almost all of them, and it just wasn't as common of a thing. There's no reason to be embarrassed. The times they have a changed!! 

I think a way to think about it for you is that, had your wife or your first wife said to you, I'd really like to keep my last name or hyphenate my last name, I cannot believe for the life of me that you would have objected, I know you wouldn't now, but I'm certain you wouldn't have then. It might have surprised you a little but I think you would have been like ueah that makes sense if that's what you want.

@SBK

Thanks!  I will definitely look into that. 

It certainly is a great question about whether math exists in the universe as an external existence, or if it came into existence when sentient species imagined it.

@SBK

Delightful indeed.

Children would read from that book to the accompaniment of themes from musicals in my personal hell 😂

@SBK

[Random size-related manhood joke]

To be fair, athletes' jerseys just have AZS UW on them, short for Akademicki Związek Sportowy Uniwersytetu Warszawskiego, Academic Sport Union of Warsaw University.

@SP

Oh yes, that does ring a bell, so maybe that's it. 
Thank you!

@Rachel

Thankfully, the popup saying you are close doesn't happen *every* time you fill in the final square.  Seemingly, if it was close enough to the last time you did that, it wouldn't show it.

This makes running through the alphabet (which seems a little like cheating, (FWIW) efficient).

@Rachel
I’ve been doing puzzles in the archive from early 2000’s this week,  and tam has appeared in quite a few 🤣
I like to run thru old Mondays, they’re easy and fun but the older ones still have some things I have to think about, so not boring at all.

@Petrol

We ordered Korean fried chicken yesterday. There was a choice of sauce. Behold! One of the options was General Tso! First time I've ever seen the name outside a NYT crossword puzzle 🤣

Also, you missed a few, like skor.

@Petrol

Good list.

Occasionally there's the odd caviar and crow.

@Mean Old Lady
“Crystal.”
 - A Few Good Men

@Jane Wheelaghan

I learned LEMMA from these puzzles. I did not understand its clue today though, but once I had most of the crosses I filled in the rest. I have been so traumatized by math any mention of it stresses me out - I actually unwittingly made a face at the mathematical clue today 🤣

@Francis

I can't stand shopping malls. A vision of the largest one in America is absolutely horrific to me 😂.

My wife's and mine favorite clothing store is at a mall, sadly. We pick weird hours to go there so there are no crowds, and we beeline for it from the parking lot. Then the trip becomes bearable 🤪.

@Francis

I know it well. Also, its Polish equivalent - łobuz - is one of my favorite words. We used it often as a nickname for Jorge the Lab - he was quite a rascal!

One more thing we share.

@SBK

Andrzej strikes me as the kind of guy that can easily swat away the premier binding element of the universe.  😂

It takes all kinds.

@Francis
Yes, "malls" or shopping centres/retail parks as we say, are not so popular here either, but I don't think they were as big as in the US. 

Humungous car parks, massive fast food "courts" (interesting re-use of the word "court") and all the same shops you see everywhere and no independents. One chain book shop. Whole families traipsing along as if they were on a holiday outing.

@Andrzej

I know how you feel--as I once felt the same way!  But instructor Mr. Hartje (later a PhD professor at the same college) changed everything for me!  He called mathematics "The Queen of Sciences." 
In a strange twist of fate, decades later we moved to a city that had a "Hartje St."....and it turned out to be that prof's birthplace and childhood home.  Karma?

@Stephen W

This is the sixth time ULTA has been in the puzzle this year, clued as a rival of Sephora four of those times.

ULTA is all over the map here, as is Sephora, but even if you don't have them in Glasgow, it should still be a gimme by now.

@Mean Old Lady

McDonald's hasn't had salads for about five years now.  (At least not in the US.)

Why?  No one went to McDonald's for salads.

@Mean Old Lady
